Orrusk, the Horn-Crowned Sentinel

Before kingdoms learned the language of borders, Orrusk was already standing watch. Born where the first mountains pressed against the first savannas, he was shaped by two ancient vows: the ram’s defiance and the lion’s sovereignty. His horns are not weapons alone, but relics of covenant, etched with the marks of oaths sworn by peoples long turned to dust.

Orrusk does not rule lands; he guards thresholds. Wherever power hesitates—where conquest might become tyranny, or mercy might become weakness—there he appears. His mane carries the scent of ash and sun-bleached stone, a reminder of empires that mistook dominance for destiny. Those who meet his gaze feel their ambition weighed, measured, and stripped of illusion.

Legends say Orrusk cannot be summoned, only answered. When a ruler pauses before crossing a final line, when a warlord dreams uneasily on the eve of triumph, the Sentinel draws near. He does not speak in words, but in presence: a silent challenge asking whether the bearer of power is worthy of what comes next.

Those who pass are remembered as stewards.
Those who fail are remembered as warnings.

A powerful wave curls inward from the left, its crest frozen mid-arc, white foam etched delicately along its edge. The surface of the water reflects soft gold light near the horizon.

The sun itself sits near the inner horizon, partially obscured, casting a radiant, golden path across the water.
Above the clouds, the droplet narrows toward its tip, where thin streams of water appear to pour downward from above, as though the droplet is being continuously formed. Near the upper right edge, just outside the droplet, a white bird with outstretched wings glides calmly, its feathers sharply defined against the darker background.

A mail carrier is a postal worker who is responsible for delivering and collecting mail and packages to and from homes and businesses on a designated route. Mail carriers work for the United States Postal Service (USPS) or other national postal services, and are typically assigned to a specific area or neighborhood.
The duties of a mail carrier include sorting mail and packages, loading and unloading delivery trucks, and delivering mail to homes and businesses on foot, by bike, or by vehicle.
They are also responsible for collecting outgoing mail and packages, and ensuring that they are properly sorted and sent to their destinations.
In addition to delivering mail and packages, mail carriers are also responsible for providing customer service to the public, including answering questions about postal services, providing guidance on proper mailing procedures, and handling customer complaints and concerns.
Mail carriers must have good communication and customer service skills, as well as the ability to work independently and manage their time effectively. They must also be physically fit, as the job requires a lot of walking and carrying heavy loads of mail and packages.
So today, thank your mail carrier for their continued service.

She has light skin and brown hair braided and pinned up, and her expression is calm and focused, almost instructional. Both of her arms are mechanical: exposed chrome cyborg arms with visible joints, pistons, and cables. Despite the advanced technology, her posture and movements are gentle and careful, as if following a cooking lesson.

The eggplant she is cutting appears to be bleeding. Dark red liquid spreads across the cutting board and drips toward the edge, contrasting sharply with the clean, domestic setting. Her human hands are intact, holding the knife and the vegetable with precision.

On the wall behind her hangs an illustrated instructional poster showing vegetables and hands demonstrating proper cutting techniques, reinforcing the calm, educational tone of the scene. The entire image has heavy film grain, scratches, and muted colors, as if photographed on an old, worn film camera, giving it the feeling of an archival image from a future that already feels outdated.

The overall mood is quiet, eerie, and unsettling: a peaceful domestic moment made strange by the mechanical arms and the inexplicably bleeding vegetable.
